peek() Method in Java Stream API

peek() is an intermediate operation that performs an action on each element without modifying the stream.

👉 It is mainly used for debugging and inspecting elements as they flow through a stream.

Method Signature
Stream<T> peek(Consumer<? super T> action)
Parameter

peek() accepts a Consumer.

A Consumer performs an action but does not return a value.

Return Value

Returns a new Stream.

This allows method chaining.

Basic Example
List<String> fruits =
        List.of("Apple", "Banana", "Orange");

fruits.stream()
      .peek(System.out::println)
      .count();

Output:

Apple
Banana
Orange
Why Use peek()?

Its main purpose is debugging.

Example:

numbers.stream()
       .filter(n -> n > 3)
       .peek(System.out::println)
       .count();

Output:

4
5
6

You can see which elements passed the filter() operation.

peek() in a Stream Pipeline
List<String> fruits =
        List.of("apple",
                "banana",
                "orange");
fruits.stream()
      .filter(s -> s.length() > 5)
      .peek(s -> System.out.println("After filter: " + s))
      .map(String::toUpperCase)
      .peek(s -> System.out.println("After map: " + s))
      .forEach(System.out::println);

Output:

After filter: banana
After map: BANANA
BANANA

After filter: orange
After map: ORANGE
ORANGE

Notice how peek() lets you inspect the stream at different stages.

peek() Does NOT Modify Elements
numbers.stream()
       .peek(System.out::println)
       .forEach(System.out::println);

The stream remains exactly the same.

But Objects Can Be Modified

If the stream contains mutable objects:

people.stream()
      .peek(person -> person.setActive(true))
      .forEach(System.out::println);

The objects themselves are changed.

⚠️ Although this is possible, it is not recommended because peek() is intended for debugging, not for changing data.

peek() Is Lazy

Nothing happens here:

numbers.stream()
       .peek(System.out::println);

There is no terminal operation.

Execution starts only after:

numbers.stream()
       .peek(System.out::println)
       .count();
peek() vs forEach()

This is a very common interview question.

peek()	forEach()
Intermediate operation	Terminal operation
Returns Stream	Returns void
Used for debugging	Used to perform final actions
Chain continues	Chain ends
Example
peek()
list.stream()
    .peek(System.out::println)
    .filter(s -> s.startsWith("A"))
    .count();

The stream continues after peek().

forEach()
list.stream()
    .forEach(System.out::println);

The stream ends here.

You cannot call another stream method after forEach().

Common Use Cases
Debugging
.peek(System.out::println)
Logging
.peek(item ->
        logger.info(item))
Checking Data Flow
stream
    .filter(...)
    .peek(...)
    .map(...)
    .peek(...)
    .collect(...);
Common Interview Questions
Is peek() terminal or intermediate?

✅ Intermediate

What functional interface does peek() use?

✅ Consumer

Does peek() modify the stream?

❌ No

What is peek() mainly used for?

✅ Debugging and inspecting elements during stream processing.

Summary
peek() performs an action on each element without changing the stream.
It is an intermediate operation.
Returns a Stream.
Uses a Consumer.
Is lazy and requires a terminal operation.
Primarily used for debugging, logging, and understanding how data flows through a stream.
